{{Hatnote|Not to be confused with the [[Beja language]], also called Bedawi.}} {{Infobox language |name=Northwest Arabian Arabic |states=[[Egypt]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Saudi Arabia]] & [[Syria]] |speakers=2.24 million |date=2015-2016 |ref=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/avl|title=Arabic, Eastern Egyptian Bedawi Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] |fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]] |fam4=[[Arabic languages|Arabic]] |fam5=[[Peninsular Arabic]] |script=[[Arabic alphabet]] |iso3=avl |image=Bedawi of the Kishon.jpg |imagecaption=A Bedawi-speaking [[Bedouin]] person, 1913 |glotto=east2690 |glottorefname=Eastern Egyptian Bedawi Arabic }}
'''Northwest Arabian Arabic''' is a [[Varieties of Arabic|variety]] of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] spoken by [[Bedouin]]s of the Sinai Peninsula, the Negev, southern Jordan, and the northwestern corner of Saudi Arabia.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Palva|first=Heikki|title=“Northwest Arabian Arabic.” Encyclopedia of Arabic language and linguistics. Vol. III. Leiden – Boston: Brill 2008, pp. 400-408.|url=https://www.academia.edu/6420713/_Northwest_Arabian_Arabic._Encyclopedia_of_Arabic_language_and_linguistics._Vol._III._Leiden_Boston_Brill_2008_pp._400-408|language=en}}</ref> In the eastern desert of Egypt, the dialect of the Maʿāzah borders the dialect of the [[Ababda people|ʿAbābdah]], who speak a dialect more closely related to Sudanese Arabic.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sylcyXHvPlcC&dq=northwest+arabian+arabic&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=A Grammar of the Bedouin Dialects of Central and Southern Sinai|last=Jong|first=Rudolf Erik De|date=2011-04-11|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004201017|language=en}}</ref>
== Characteristics == The Northwest Arabian Arabic dialects share a number of features distinguishing them from the North Arabian Bedouin dialects:<ref name=":0" />
# Absence of ''tanwīn'' and its residues. # Absence of affricated variants of /g/ (< */q/) and /k/. # Absence of final /n/ in the imperfect, 2nd person feminine singular, 2nd person masculine plural, and 3rd person masculine plural. # The pronominal suffix of the 2nd person masculine plural is -''ku'' (-''kuw''). # The use of the locative preposition ''fi'' (''fiy'').
== Levantine Bedawi == '''Levantine Bedawi''' is spoken in the eastern area of Jordan,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/avl|title=Arabic, Eastern Egyptian Bedawi Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref> in the southwestern corner of Syria and in the Bedouin regions of Egypt (on the northern and southern coast of the [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/map/EGLY|title=Egypt and Libya|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref>
